    <h1>Visualizing Pathfinding on OpenStreetMap</h1>
    <p class="dek">A Python experiment for watching BFS, Dijkstra, A*, and Greedy Best-First Search move through real road networks.</p>
    <div class="byline"><img class="avatar" src="assets/nishon-tandukar.jpg" alt=""><div><strong>Nishon Tandukar</strong><span>Geospatial Software Engineer</span></div></div>
  </header>

  <figure class="hero-visual">
    <img src="assets/osm-pathfinding-astar.gif" alt="Animated A-star pathfinding search expanding across an OpenStreetMap road network">
    <figcaption><span>A* exploring a real road graph before highlighting the final route.</span><a href="https://github.com/konishon/osm-pathfinding-visualizer" target="_blank" rel="noopener">View the project on GitHub <span class="ui-icon icon-external-link" aria-hidden="true"></span></a></figcaption>
  </figure>

  <div class="layout shell">
    <aside class="toc" aria-label="Article contents">
      <strong>In this article</strong>
      <a href="#why">From grids to streets</a><a href="#pipeline">Preparing the graph</a><a href="#algorithms">Search strategies</a><a href="#visuals">Rendering the search</a><a href="#sound">Adding sound</a><a href="#lessons">Implementation notes</a><a href="#run">Run the project</a>
    </aside>
    <article>
      <p class="lead">I had seen plenty of pathfinding demos on square grids. I wanted to watch the same algorithms work on streets I could recognise.</p>
      <p><a href="https://github.com/konishon/osm-pathfinding-visualizer" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><u>OSM Pathfinding Visualizer</u></a> downloads a road network from OpenStreetMap, runs a selected search algorithm, and animates the explored edges and final route. It supports 2D and 3D views, live playback, and GIF or MP4 export.</p>

      <h2 id="why">From grids to streets</h2>
      <p>A grid hides several decisions that appear immediately on a road graph. Intersections have uneven degree, roads curve, and edge lengths vary. “Shortest” can mean the fewest road segments or the least distance travelled.</p>
      <p>OpenStreetMap supplies that messiness. BFS counts graph hops. Dijkstra accumulates road length. A* adds a straight-line heuristic toward the destination. Greedy Best-First Search follows the heuristic without accounting for the distance already travelled. Running them over one street network makes the differences visible.</p>

      <h2 id="pipeline">Preparing the graph</h2>
      <p>The tool starts with two latitude–longitude pairs. A configuration object creates a bounding box around them and adjusts it to a vertical 9:16 frame. OSMnx then downloads the drivable street network and turns it into a NetworkX graph.</p>
      <div class="flow">Start and end coordinates
        ↓
OSM bounding box
        ↓
Drivable street graph from OSMnx
        ↓
Projected graph in metres
        ↓
Nearest start and destination nodes
        ↓
Search traversal and final route</div>
      <p>I project the downloaded graph before routing. The edge weights and A* heuristic then operate in metres instead of raw longitude and latitude. The graph and nearby map features are cached by bounding box, which cuts out repeated OSM requests while I test different algorithms.</p>
      <p>For the 2D view, I also request buildings, water, parks, forests, grass, and related OSM features. They do not affect routing; they are background layers.</p>

      <h2 id="algorithms">Search strategies</h2>
      <div class="algorithm-grid">
        <div class="algorithm"><strong>Breadth-First Search</strong><p>Expands evenly and finds the route with the fewest graph edges. It ignores road length.</p></div>
        <div class="algorithm"><strong>Dijkstra</strong><p>Prioritizes accumulated edge length and guarantees the shortest weighted route.</p></div>
        <div class="algorithm"><strong>A*</strong><p>Adds a Euclidean heuristic to the travelled distance, guiding the search toward the target.</p></div>
        <div class="algorithm"><strong>Greedy Best-First</strong><p>Chases the heuristic directly. It can be fast, but its route is not guaranteed to be shortest.</p></div>
      </div>
      <p>Each traversal is a Python generator. It yields an edge when the algorithm explores it, so the animation can consume the search incrementally instead of waiting for a completed path.</p>
      <div class="callout"><strong>Two outputs</strong><code>explored_edges</code> records the search process. The route is calculated separately and drawn only after the search phase.</div>

      <h2 id="visuals">Rendering the search</h2>
      <p>Matplotlib collections keep the base road network fixed while the explored-edge collection grows. The search is blue; the final route appears in green during the last part of the animation.</p>
      <p>In 3D mode, I place roads, explored edges, and the route at slightly different z-levels and tilt the camera. The 2D renderer stays top-down and includes the contextual OSM layers. The command-line interface can open an interactive window, render a static preview, or export an MP4 or GIF.</p>

      <h2 id="sound">Making search audible</h2>
      <p>I added sound after the visual animation was working. During exploration, short sine-wave beeps climb from 200 to 1,200 Hz. Reaching the destination triggers a rising sweep and a decaying two-frequency tone.</p>
      <p>Interactive mode sends the waveforms to Pygame. Export mode mixes NumPy waveforms into a mono buffer, writes a temporary WAV file, and asks FFmpeg to merge it with the rendered video. Because the audio is generated from frame numbers, it stays synchronized without separate sound files.</p>

      <h2 id="lessons">Implementation notes</h2>
      <p>BFS minimizes edge count, while Dijkstra and A* minimize road length. On a real network, a route with fewer named streets can still be longer.</p>
      <p>The generator interface ended up being the most useful design choice. The same edge stream drives drawing and sound, and it is straightforward to inspect in tests.</p>
      <p>Greedy Best-First Search needed separate handling. I store parent pointers during its traversal and reconstruct the route it actually took. The reconstruction rejects missing links and cycles instead of falling back to an optimal NetworkX route that the greedy search never found.</p>
      <p>Most of the wait time comes from downloading and processing OSM data, not from running the search. The cache made side-by-side algorithm testing practical.</p>

      <h2 id="run">Run it yourself</h2>
      <p>The project uses Poetry and Python. FFmpeg is only required for video export.</p>
      <pre><code>poetry install
poetry run path-viz --algo astar --dim 3d

# Export a GIF
poetry run path-viz \
  --mode export \
  --algo dijkstra \
  --dim 2d \
  --duration 10 \
  --output route.gif</code></pre>
      <p>Custom start and end coordinates can be supplied from the command line, making it possible to compare the algorithms in any area covered by OpenStreetMap.</p>
      <p><a class="repo-link" href="https://github.com/konishon/osm-pathfinding-visualizer" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Explore the source on GitHub <span class="ui-icon icon-external-link" aria-hidden="true"></span></a></p>
    </article>
